Considering that this period coincides with the onset of winter in a New England locale, it's plausible that the dip in bicycle and pedestrian commuting played a role. Additionally, December marks the end of the academic semester, leaving many preoccupied with final tasks and grading, which could have led to the log submisions being overlooked. Furthermore, December is a holiday month, with a subsequent break for both students and faculty, reducing campus attendance significantly. The resumption of classes in late January might also explain the low number of February submissions. However, the dip in February remains unexplained. It's possible that the initial enthusiasm for such projects often wanes over time. To address this, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, which did manage to boost log submissions. Thus, one challenge was sustaining project momentum amidst natural ebbs and academic breaks.

Another significant hurdle for this project, and similar initiatives, is the widespread preference for driving. This behavior is deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, it's crucial to offer incentives to encourage alternative modes of commuting. We offered various prizes, including gift cards for local businesses and even a few national chains. It's intriguing to consider whether even larger prizes, such as bicycles or hybrid/electric cars, could have further increased participation. The value of these prizes remained consistent throughout the project. However, increasing their value over time could have potentially boosted engagement. While gift cards seemed sufficient at the outset, announcing more substantial prizes in December and January might have enticed more participation and mitigated the initial decline.

An Exchange Traded Fund (ETF) is a financial product that mirrors an index, commodity, or a collection of assets, similar to an index fund, yet offers more flexibility as it trades like a stock on an exchange. Unlike mutual funds, ETFs provide the benefits of diversification and ownership akin to single stocks, including short selling, margin buying, and purchasing as little as one share per transaction. Despite these advantages, ETFs generally have lower expense ratios compared to mutual funds. However, there are trade-offs; every ETF transaction incurs a commission, similar to stock trades. Another plus side is the broad range of available funds. It is prudent for discerning investors to scrutinize these claimed benefits, ensuring they exist and are substantial. For this study, we examine ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings, accounting for 63.58% of its assets, to assess whether owning a single ETF yields benefits similar to a diversified portfolio of these ten stocks. We also explore if there's a more optimal stock configuration offering a better Sharpe ratio or return.

A notable work in Edgar Allan Poe's oeuvre is "Dream-Land," which he esteemed amongst his finest creations. In this piece, Poe deploys the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, a reference traced by Mabbott back to Virgil. Virgil, in turn, employed this term to denote an island beyond the northern reaches of Britain, an extremity of the known world to the Greeks. While Virgil's usage is undeniable, a more contemporary influence could be acknowledged. Poe, fascinated by German literature, would have encountered this term through his readings of Goethe.

This is of significance as it illuminates Poe's intimacy with Goethe's works. Karl J. Arndt, in his tome "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," draws parallel lines between the two poets' compositions, suggesting Poe's imitation of Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature lauds Goethe as a luminary of poetic drama, particularly for his magnum opus "Faust," released in two installments, the first in 1808 and the second upon his death in 1832. Within the latter part of Faust, a short poem entitled "The King of Thule" appears, depicting a monarch whose life unravels after the death of his wife and the gifting of a goblet. Driven to despair, he ultimately sacrifices himself and his possessions, save for the goblet, which he casts into the sea. This narrative bears a striking resemblance to the emotional landscape of "Dream-Land," with its melancholic speaker haunted and desolate, echoing Poe's grief and possibly his own struggles with alcohol.

Poe's invocation of Thule is not isolated to "Dream-Land"; he employs the phrase "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum." The use of the term as bookends in "Dream-Land" further underscores its significance. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces, with the latter's dark, lonely Thule mirroring Goethe's desolate king and his own poignant loss. The speaker's description of this realm as a haunted, colorless, and shaded world resonates with the despair of Goethe's king, as if Poe had stepped into Goethe's poem.

Goethe's importance cannot be overstated; Poe would have been familiar with his works, at the very least through Tennyson's admiration for him. When queried about his esteem for Tennyson, Poe also expressed his respect for Goethe, likely having encountered his works through various reproductions.

In accordance with California law, could a customer injured following a slip-and-fall on a spilled applesauce in a supermarket be awarded punitive damages by demonstrating that the store manager acted with ill intent because he was informed of the spill twice and did not clear it for half an hour due to dining?A judge is unlikely to promptly dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To establish that punitive damages are merited, a plaintiff must present evidence that the defendant’s actions were carried out with willful and deliberate disregard for probable harm, as well as evidence that the conduct was reprehensible. Palmer can argue that Martin should have anticipated the potential harm of not cleaning the spill, given that multiple incidents of slipping had occurred prior to her accident, and despite this knowledge, he failed to address the issue. While Palmer's assertion that Martin's actions were reprehensible is less convincing, it remains reasonable under the circumstances, considering six slip-and-fall incidents had transpired in 2009 and Martin still failed to implement adequate measures to ensure store safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, Richard Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, notified his supervisor, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin replied that he was on his dinner break and "didn't have time to handle customer complaints." At 5:15 PM, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also informed Mr. Martin about the spill, and he responded similarly. By 5:30 PM on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a severe back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five separate slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D's in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for both compensatory and punitive damages due to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial dismissal of the punitive damage claim.

Under California law, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising from a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or, in the absence of intent, conduct that must be "despicable" and committed with "willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." id. at § (c)(1). Courts have labeled conduct as malicious when, knowing the probable harmful consequences, a defendant deliberately failed to avoid them. Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

Nearly four years ago, I encountered a course on Islam at CBC, where the class frequently debated the contentious issue of whether Islam is inherently hostile. The relevance of this discussion appears to have grown since then, particularly in light of recent global events and the shifting public perception of Islam in the United States. In the aftermath of 9/11, for instance, there's been a noticeable shift from a hostile portrayal of Islam and extremism to an extreme form of tolerance, even to the extent that a candidate with a Muslim background, such as President Barack Obama, could be elected in 2008.

The Biography of the Prophet Muhammad captures my curiosity as the narrative diverges from historical accounts of his life. In my previous understanding, Muhammad was perceived as a conqueror who compelled tribes to adopt Islam through force. However, the biography portrays him as a martyr who endured misunderstanding and humility. This version of events implies that people increasingly sought out Muhammad after witnessing his teachings' truth.

Certain parallels between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' attributed to Muhammad also intrigue me. For example, the account of Muhammad multiplying mutton and milk to feed forty men echoes the biblical story of Jesus' feeding of the five thousand. This style of storytelling suggests a deliberate attempt to portray Muhammad as a humble prophet, emphasizing his acts of truth and miracle, rather than necessitating proofs. This approach, I believe, diminishes the significance of Jesus' life and miracles.

Moreover, many stories in the biography seem to serve an agenda of demonstrating the voluntary nature of conversions to Islam. These accounts often rely on third-party accounts, with information passed down through multiple intermediaries. While intended to bolster the credibility of the stories, this method can actually undermine their authenticity, as it adds layers of hearsay.

What troubles me most is the portrayal of Muhammad as a pious, wise, and gentle leader. Historical records contradict this depiction, suggesting a more complex and sometimes harsh figure. Given this disparity, it makes me wonder if modern Muslims are aware of the full spectrum of Muhammad's history and rise to power.

The precepts and convictions espoused by Jesus during his tenure were promptly cast aside as Christian thought evolved post-mortem. A cursory examination of this trajectory reveals a steady drift away from the origin. The contemporary world exhibits an increasing consciousness and an unparalleled progressive inclination. While the traditionalists persist, their influence may not be extensive enough to dictate the whole. Among the adherents, historical acumen will surge in the coming years, sparking a desire to discern the principles appended to Christianity over time from the authentic intentions of its namesake. This pendulum swing may take decades or even centuries, but the reversal is assured: Christianity will revert to its primordial form. A swell will emerge, peeling back the layers of doctrine, much like the hands of a clock turning backward, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced to humanity remains. When this wave sweeps across the United States and Europe, swaying the masses to revere as if we were living in Jesus' time, following solely his thoughts, the institutional church will remain steadfast in guiding the way. However, with the theological clock reversed, the proliferation of diversity within Christendom will diminish, giving way to uniformity of belief and practice. Regional, denominational, and sectarian differences will yield to growing similarities. History is replete with such reversals. Case in point: Christians were once persecuted and killed by the Roman Empire, yet the empire later became a Christian power. Our nation has evolved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The upcoming reversal in Christianity will unfold, undoing history to return to the source and diminishing diversity in its path. This progression hinges on an interpretative approach to Jesus' words, viewing them as metaphorical rather than literal. So, what has transpired since Jesus' life?
       A deep dive into history reveals that Judaism, the theological precursor to Christianity, was predominant. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were the bedrock of the religion by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish populace was not unified; they were divided into groups such as Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common people.

The narrative of "The Jungle" reveals the inherent inclination of humans to prioritize self-interest and disregard the well-being of others. In Sinclair's world, the executives and overseers of the sprawling factories represent this self-serving nature. They are solely focused on amassing power and wealth, oblivious to the havoc their actions wreak. The author employs vivid imagery to highlight the consequences of their unchecked ambition, "The buildings stood tall and proud against the sky, their smokestacks spewing clouds of smoke that stretched towards infinity." This visual is a stark depiction of the environmental devastation caused by their relentless pursuit of progress.

The indifference extends to the employees, who are mere tools in their pursuit of profit. Workers are subject to grueling schedules and sudden layoffs without recompense, all in the name of maximizing efficiency. In the absence of protective regulations, exploitation was rife. The employers held a stranglehold over their workforce, much like slave owners, with workers having no recourse or support. The narrative hints at the dehumanizing conditions, "The workers, many of whom were immigrants, lived in a perpetual state of poverty and desperation, their lives contingent on the caprices of their masters." Unions, intended to advocate for the workers, often exacerbated the suffering, further entrenching the system of exploitation that defined Packingtown.

Multiple authors deploy varied methods to evoke specific sentiments in their audiences. Among these techniques, F. Scott Fitzgerald employs several in his novel "The Great Gatsby." Occasionally, he pairs adjectives with nouns in unconventional ways to impart a certain vibe around a subject. He also ascribes significance to symbols and uses them to achieve the same effect. In his work, Fitzgerald assigns meaning to numerous colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. He builds up these meanings and subsequently employs them to trigger certain emotions when encountering significant objects.

In "The Great Gatsby," Fitzgerald associates white/gray with uniformity, with white connoting elegance and sophistication, and gray symbolizing age and weariness. He establishes this association early in the novel through frequent references to both colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently "in white," and even Nick dons "white flannels" at Gatsby's party. Tom wears a "white shirt" when meeting Myrtle. The only departure from this white prevalence occurs when Nick is first introduced to Gatsby's party, where the halls are "gaudy with primary colors." This color coding extends to various mundane subjects, such as the "white chasms of lower New York," "gray names" on Nick's timetable, and even the "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes. Fitzgerald further reinforces this uniformity by describing common people or places in these colors, including the "white girlhood" of Jordan and Daisy, and the "gray" Italian child on the railroad.

Once Fitzgerald has established these meanings, he uses white/gray to signify unimportance or uniformity. This technique begins with Daisy, who, after a prolonged absence of either color in the story, is described as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster." Readers begin to perceive Daisy as less of a character and more like a uniform addition, a mere object of Gatsby's desire. This use of color continues with references to a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" and her being in a "white" dress before Tom and Gatsby's confrontation.

San Diego County, due to its temperate and sunny climate, is a notable agricultural powerhouse. Crops that flourish here include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There's a strong demand for organic, community-supported agriculture in the region, with several local organizations boasting lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also in high demand. Many organic farms not only offer tours of their operations but also facilitate activities like hiking and birdwatching. Such enterprises can leverage government programs to enhance habitat quality, create recreational spaces, and generate income or educational opportunities. Organic farming, while more demanding in terms of labor and management, can foster greater biodiversity. However, it may also incur higher costs and experience greater crop losses. Non-organic practices beneficial to wildlife can also add to labor expenses. Thus, a landowner in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expertise to balance profits and habitat conservation. The selected land is a 160-acre parcel near Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. It's part of the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion, home to over a hundred species, many endangered or declining. The area has a rich history, having been inhabited by Native Americans and later used by cattle ranchers. The property was originally part of a homestead and likely used for grazing and wood production. Researching available government programs and exploring a nearby organic farm provided insights into potential cost mitigation and wildlife-friendly farming practices.

Cultural nuances are pivotal in any negotiation. Culture isn't just about what it is, but also what it isn't and the meaning behind it. It's diverse, multifaceted, and not universally uniform. Generalizations like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are too broad and oversimplified. While understanding cultural norms is beneficial, it's more productive to grasp how a culture's values influence negotiation dynamics. When interacting with foreign cultures, one tends to compare them to their own, which can be insightful but also misleading.

Understanding a foreign culture or mindset might involve exploring its history or recognizing its biases. Instead of attempting to alter or judge a culture, one should accept it as is and operate within its parameters, especially when negotiations are involved, and particularly if one is in a weaker position. Being on "foreign" turf necessitates respect for traditions and beliefs, which can transcend cultural hurdles and facilitate negotiations.

Culture isn't confined to national or international contexts. Many companies within a nation develop their own unique corporate culture, evident in dress codes, communication styles, hiring practices, and attitudes towards philanthropy. Even within a single nation, corporate cultures can vary widely, as seen in the differences between American companies. Some cultures appear more uniform, but a closer look reveals their varied nuances.

Values are crucial to decipher, as they explain why a culture behaves a certain way. If preserving face or promoting harmony is valued, a negotiator won't publicly embarrass their company. Conversely, a culture that prioritizes aggressive negotiations won't settle quickly. Recognizing these cultural priorities before negotiations is essential, but learning about the other party's personal values can enhance negotiation effectiveness.

"In the Book of Psalms, it is written, 'The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This phrase is central to St. Anselm's reasoning regarding the existence of a deity, and it is also echoed by Thomas Aquinas. To evaluate their arguments, we'll presume they both adhere to the monotheistic belief of the Bible, as they are both defending the same divine figure. This assumption simplifies our comparison, as both arguments are rooted in the same concept of God.

In examining Anselm's approach, we find that it centers on an inner search for truth. He posits that God's existence can be derived from our understanding, as we cannot imagine His nonexistence. This concept, though complex and sometimes unclear, suggests that God's reality is intrinsic to our minds. Thus, the proof lies within us, requiring no external verification. This notion aligns with Christian teachings, which often refer to this as faith.

Conversely, Aquinas advocates for a rationale based on logical reasoning and empirical evidence. His method avoids faith entirely, making it more appealing for converting non-believers, as it relies on reasoning rather than accepting something unprovable. Aquinas presents five logical arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each argument illustrates that God's existence is a necessary logical conclusion. If one lacks a single piece of a puzzle but can deduce its features and existence from the rest, this is analogous to Aquinas' logical arguments for God's existence.

In the dawn of the fifth or sixth century BCE, a monarch-to-be, later revered as the Buddha, drew breath. His life's journey saw him forsake the world and achieve enlightenment, sparking the birth of Buddhism, with its most traditional branch being Theravada Buddhism. The religion, now over two and a half millennia old, bears little resemblance to its founders' time. This can be observed in Theravada-majority Sri Lanka, where the annual Maha Silavimokkha ceremony is celebrated. Both monks and laypeople participate, despite no mention of such rituals in the Buddha's teachings. These modifications extend from the most outward traditions to the religion's core beliefs. The Theravada Buddhist community, spanning both monastic and lay domains, has adapted its principles over time, influenced by both internal and external factors, both friendly and adversarial.
	To navigate this discussion, several key terms will be frequently used. Here, internal forces refer to influences stemming from within the Buddhist community, regardless of monastic affiliation. External forces encompass those from non-Buddhist sources. Hostile forces are those that pose a threat or intend to harm the Buddhist community, often due to misconceptions about Buddhism. Benign forces, meanwhile, do not wish to harm or aid the community, but may inadvertently do so. These terms will recur throughout this discussion.
	First, let us examine the bedrock of Theravada Buddhism—the doctrines that underpin it. Buddhists take refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma comprises the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka includes the religion's metaphysical aspects, such as Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (inherent suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Recognizing these principles allows one to escape Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, ending lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) upon enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth life's rules. Laypeople adhere to five precepts: I will not kill, I will not lie, I will not steal, I will not misbehave sexually, and I will not consume intoxicants. Monks follow many more rules. The most foundational doctrinal tenet is the four noble truths: life is Dukkha (suffering), attachment causes suffering, and suffering can be overcome.

The United States of America and Mexico once faced a protracted dispute lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145) The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States emerged victorious and gained control of Texas and the southwestern territories. Multiple skirmishes occurred between these nations, tapering off just prior to the First World War. The rivalry stemmed from disagreements over religion, culture, and material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

This scenario mirrors many other nations that have ongoing rivalries with their neighbors. Shared borders often lead to conflicting interests, fostering rivalries. The United States and Mexico are no exception. David M. Pletcher (1977) asserts that “Only in Mexico and Cuba does one find enduring American diplomatic issues” (p. 41). Indeed, both nations, being geographically close to the United States, have historically been rivals, unlike many other Latin American countries that have maintained good relations with the United States.

Religious tensions have long divided these nations, a problem that has plagued many throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) notes that “While in the twentieth century Americans opposed fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they opposed Catholicism and monarchy” (p.86). Similar to the Cold War, the rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, this conflict was partly ideological and partly a competition over vital interests. However, the ideological differences were rooted in religious preferences rather than political systems. The distrust stemmed from earlier colonial tensions between the English and Spanish, which hindered the development of peaceful diplomatic relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) enumerate 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States over the 57-year rivalry period. Most of these disputes centered around territorial issues, with border raids and frontier problems being significant concerns. Outlaw activities from American border towns into Mexican territory posed a major challenge, persisting until both nations strengthened their military presence on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry began to subside as Mexico became increasingly reliant on the United States. It finally concluded with a shift in American ambitions, from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico, towards the end of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, an unforeseen and unanticipated affliction rendered me incapacitated, an illness that I had never been made aware of. At that time, I was pursuing a career as a nurse, a choice made due to a profound desire for the safety and stability that I had lacked during my childhood. "You'll always find employment; people will always require care" became the mantra that echoed through my adolescence and beyond. Thus, even though my heart yearned to be a scientist or a journalist, preferably a blend of both, I chose nursing.

However, here I am: 46 years old, unmarried, possessing no financial reserves, and unable to work. To this day, I am disabled, and after 15 years of subsisting on Social Security Disability, I have nothing left that is truly mine. I manage to endure, but every day is a battle, an assault on my security, safety, and self-worth. Nothing is certain anymore, yet there is one truth that stands unwavering: I could not have persevered for this long without the support of my kin and a few steadfast friends. And let me assure you, when calamity truly strikes, you feel far from invincible.

The crux of my argument is that life is full of unpredictability, both large and small. There are no guarantees, and despite our best efforts, some challenges are simply too immense to overcome alone.

I am in complete agreement that we must cease placing all our hopes in the crumbling, leaky vessel that is our government. But I would much prefer to see Americans reclaim their trust in one another, learning to aid each other and to request assistance, rather than each of us retreating to our own backyards to construct fallout shelters.

The conservatives in the U.S. often extol the virtues of "rugged individualism" that supposedly built this nation; however, the resilience of our forefathers in times of hardship was not born of rugged individualism, but of compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who traversed the Rocky Mountains in wagon trains did not reach the coast by relying solely on their own strength.

As such, I wholeheartedly recommend preparing for emergencies. I am well-equipped with a disaster kit, first-aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting for my windows in the event of a biological attack. I possess multiple flashlights and an abundance of batteries, numerous candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods. If you have the land and resources to maintain a small farm and preserve your own food, do so. It is a commendable endeavor, as is the installation of a wood stove, provided you do not reside in an apartment.

But alongside these preparations, it is essential to forge connections with your neighbors.

What drives the evolutionary trajectory of organisms? Are there inherent restrictions or constraints that steer the course of biological change? As D'Arcy Thompson acknowledged in 1917, "Even now the zoologist has barely begun to dream of defining in mathematical terms the simplest organic forms." While this sentiment still holds true, advancements in mathematical modeling have been made in understanding mollusk skeletogenesis throughout ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research aims to unravel the mechanisms behind the direction and scale of evolutionary-developmental changes in Prunum by integrating mathematical modeling with experimental studies. Using X-ray images of Prunum species, we identified quantitative parameters to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies with the software CerioShell (Stone, 1995). These models help interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum, complementing experimental and descriptive studies to illuminate macroevolutionary events within this group.

A shell can be visualized as a cylindrical structure that evolves over time through 360 degrees of space, with each loop or turn referred to as a whorl, spiraling around an imaginary central axis, the columella. The rate at which whorls expand varies, with a continuous boundary separating each one, called a suture. Typically, the largest whorl, known as the body whorl, is the last. The spire encompasses all whorls except the last, with the apex at the top and base at the bottom. The aperture, an opening, is where the animal exits the shell.

Shells can be examined from various angles: apical (top view), basal (bottom view), apertural (front view), and abapertural (side view). The standard orientation places the aperture toward the viewer with the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, start by viewing the shell from the apical perspective and locating the first suture. Draw a line dividing the shell into two sections. Count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl if necessary.

A shell can be perceived as a series of apertures tracking the animal's growth over time and space. The path of the aperture can be tracked using coordinates of each whorl's aperture center and its horizontal and vertical radii.

This trajectory can be represented both graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical formulation is established, parameters can be altered to modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

For the past decade, neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has shown little fluctuation. Despite Indonesia's progress towards several Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, improvements for child and maternal health remain insufficient to meet 2015 targets. Various factors contribute to these shortfalls, suggesting the need to bolster the healthcare system rather than solely focusing on specific interventions.

Indonesia has seen an increase in the number of births attended by skilled personnel, with 72% now meeting this criterion. However, this figure includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot administer medical interventions during complex pregnancies, leading to maternal deaths from hemorrhage. Thus, these improvements are somewhat deceptive and further work is needed. Additionally, the proportion of children under five receiving professional treatment for diarrhea has declined. Data on postnatal care is incomplete but shows low rates nationwide.

Cesarian-section rates remain low, at 4%, with urban areas having a 7% rate compared to 2% in rural areas. This disparity highlights the issue of limited healthcare access, primarily in rural regions. Moreover, there's a 27% gap in service usage between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles, indicating the poor struggle more to access healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

Looking forward to enhancing neonatal and maternal health indicators, the crucial question is how best to tackle the gap in service delivery. Should Indonesia adopt targeted program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall healthcare system without focusing solely on pre- and post-pregnancy care? While programmatic approaches offer clear, manageable objectives and quicker results, they can also lead to funding diversion and duplication of services. For instance, heavy investment in one sector, like HIV/AIDS, can divert resources from another like family planning.

The Victorian period's literature is renowned for its meticulous detail and preoccupation with the upper class. Contrary to this, novels such as Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights diverge, showcasing elements of intrigue and eccentricity that are atypical of the era. These novels use mystery, often through dream sequences or dreamlike states, to delve deeper into characters' motivations and emotions. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences reveal Oliver's inner turmoil, his awareness of his plight, and his inability to control his circumstances. The shooting scene in Chapter 28, a vivid dreamlike sequence, demonstrates Oliver's lack of control and the dire straits of his health. The passage emphasizes his desperation and the relentless fear and pain he experiences during the shooting, even as he is removed from the immediate shock. The incident suggests that Oliver's misfortune is not of his own making, reinforcing his helplessness and growing sense of defeat, as if old Fagin is breaking his spirit and stripping him of the ability to react. The shooting highlights the pervasive influence of his fate, which is not under his control. This is underscored by Oliver's inability to muster any response, even in the face of life-threatening danger. The shooting, in this context, serves as a stark reminder of his powerlessness and the extent to which he is a pawn in the hands of external forces.

A few years back, I participated in an after-school program assisting elementary-aged students with their studies. I offered my best efforts to help them in their areas of need, with a particular aptitude for English and reading. An instructor approached me, requesting my assistance with a young boy named Adrian, presumably in third or fourth grade, who was grappling with reading difficulties. It became evident that something was amiss; his pronunciation of certain letters was flawless, while others were completely off. Intrigued, I discovered that Adrian, of Latino descent, spoke English flawlessly but struggled with the alphabet. This revelation occurred when I encountered Adrian's mother, who only communicated in Spanish. Despite my rudimentary Spanish skills, we managed to convey our thoughts. It dawned on me that Adrian could read well but lacked familiarity with the English alphabet. I hope Adrian's reading skills improved since then.

I share this anecdote to highlight the challenges posed by language barriers in schools, especially in California. It also illustrates the complexity of reading difficulties, even for students who speak English fluently. The issue is evident, so what is the solution? In Adrian's case, English reading tutoring, particularly focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation, proved effective. However, for students with limited English proficiency, the solution is multifaceted and complex. No single approach can solve the problem; the key lies in combining various strategies.

Firstly, the dual language system is a promising approach. Not only for Spanish-speaking students, but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." There's a misconception that this system wastes resources and benefits only a select few. This is untrue. If implemented as the norm, all children would reap its benefits. How can we achieve this? Requiring all teachers to be bilingual is impractical. Instead, special bilingual aids or tutors could be employed to support this system.

Since childhood, we're often introduced to the notion that there's something greater than ourselves, something beyond our grasp. Some of us attend religious institutions to learn about it, while others explore within ourselves for answers. Many of us inherit and embrace the faiths passed down by our ancestors, while others reject them entirely. Our paths differ, each one carving out a unique spiritual identity. We all search for guidance in the darkness to guide us into the light.

My father, when I inquired about his favorite bird, replied "A cardinal." We sat on our porch, the rain drumming on the tin roof above, as we shared cigarettes. The gutters emptied the rain, drowning the plants around us. He gazed into the rain, lost in thought, thinner and weaker than I remembered. His hair had thinned, his clothes loose on his frame. He stared ahead, evading my gaze. I felt isolated, anxious, unable to discuss my fears with him. I embraced him, moved my chair closer, and gazed with him into the June twilight rain.

My father passed in December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The treatments prolonged his suffering, but only by a few months. I couldn't watch him depart this life. I wanted to honor his memory as he lived, not as he died. I curled up in bed for three days, awaiting news.

No one contacted me.

The conventional "Gothic Novel" is essentially a synthesis of "old" and "new" elements, as elucidated by Ian Watt in his seminal work, The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This literary mode has been simultaneously maligned and celebrated, with critics alternately accusing it of superficiality and lauding its 'terrifying grandeur' (Burke). The inception of the "Gothic Novel" can be traced back to The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole, which blended both archaic and contemporary romance tropes to birth the fledgling Gothic genre and introduce a novel method of storytelling. Walpole deftly incorporated old theatrical elements and modern mimetic techniques in his "Gothic Tale" (Walpole 4), creating a unique fusion that drew from medieval Gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Despite the word "gothic" being used to denote various peoples, styles, and eras, it was often viewed as antiquated or unsophisticated amidst the literary and societal advancements of the time. The marriage of these 'Gothic' elements with the novel form, which permitted readers a more intimate glimpse into characters' psyches, ensured the Gothic genre's enduring appeal and its ability to feel both obsolete and fresh to readers removed from its original context.

A notable theme in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto, recasts the medieval ideal of knightly training, embodying both the retention and transformation of this tradition. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers because it represents the quintessential knight—brave, honorable, and skilled—a stark contrast to the perceived moral decay of contemporary society. By adopting chivalric concepts and manners, the "Gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, foreshadowing the evolution of Gothic into Romanticism and serving as a means to critique the present. Walpole, writing amidst political turmoil and possibly harboring frustrations with his contemporaries, may have felt that the moral integrity and inherent goodness of the medieval era had been lost in the 'present' society. This sentiment is evident in his portrayal of various characters, notably Frederic, who encapsulates numerous chivalric traits. Before meeting Frederic, the reader is made aware of his chivalric qualities; he is described as:

The description of him is replete with chivalric images; Frederic is, foremost, a prince, having endured tragedy and been presumed killed by infidels. The figure of the 'brave, courteous knight' is exaggerated, exemplifying the soon-to-be iconic Gothic trope of excess (66).

The shipment of products, from inception to delivery, constitutes the flow of a supply chain. This concept was introduced in 1982 by a certain consultant named Keith Oliver. He posited that supply chain management encompasses the planning, execution, and oversight of this process to meet customer needs swiftly and effectively. Six fundamental components comprise a supply chain: production, sourcing, stockpiling, placement, transit, and information. Business leaders leverage these elements to offer optimal customer service.

Production, the first phase, serves as the cornerstone of the supply chain. It dictates the timing, rationale, site, and method of production. To understand customer preferences, managers scrutinize market trends. This analysis enables them to determine which products to produce and in what quantities. Once these decisions are made, managers select the most suitable location for production, considering volume, quality, and customer satisfaction. Post-location selection, managers allocate workloads and maintain equipment. Production is pivotal, with meticulous planning crucial to avoid time and cost discrepancies in the long term. My previous experience at Wal-Mart and Target underscores the importance of structured processes. Detailed layouts and procedures, from employee attire to shipment receipts, foster seamless operations and minimize confusion.

The second key component of supply chain management is sourcing. It involves strategic decisions to define a facility's core capabilities and forge partnerships with external entities. A single product may have multiple production divisions, each with unique equipment, personnel, and specialties. Managers must identify the most suitable division for each production segment. They may also opt to outsource work to external companies to accelerate delivery times, maintain quality, and reduce costs.

Standing on a bustling street corner, Ellen Page, the actress known for her role in Juno, holds a makeshift sign with a peculiar message. The sign reads, "Adolf Hitler, alive and well in Myanmar." This Southeast Asian country, once known as Burma, has long been governed by a brutal military regime that seized power in 1962. In 2007, monks led a wave of street protests, earning the moniker "The Saffron Revolution." Initially, the government permitted peaceful gatherings, but as protests grew, so did the violence, with the military targeting monasteries. Journalists were imprisoned or killed, including Kenji Nagai, who was murdered on September 27, 2007, for merely covering the demonstrations. Officially, 13 people were killed, but defecting Colonel Hla Win claimed thousands more died. This is not an isolated event. Throughout history, leaders have suppressed dissent to maintain their grip on power. From ancient Roman emperors to modern-day heads of state, the pattern is distressingly familiar.

Notable incidents include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where hundreds to thousands were killed, and the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militias, aided by the government, murdered Tutsis and political moderates regardless of ethnicity. Adolf Hitler's campaign of genocide against Jews during World War II stands as a stark reminder of the horrors that can occur when such ideologies are unchecked.

Duke Ellington's enduring influence on jazz music is attributable to his extensive career and skill in steering his orchestra. While Ellington's keyboard prowess is often understated in many of the compositions analyzed, his forte as a composer shines in his ability to write intricate and multifaceted pieces that highlight individual band member's skills. He crafted a structure that allowed soloists to improvise freely, while simultaneously composing tightly arranged pieces that emphasized specific member's styles to convey musical themes. This approach, which also emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, resulted in many groundbreaking and brilliant jazz works.

The Grove Music dictionary highlights Ellington's innovative sound and use of voice as an instrument, citing "Creole Love Call" as an early example. This slow, twelve-bar blues piece features six choruses, each showcasing unique solo performances and call-and-response patterns between the voice and reeds, brass, and piano. Ellington's mastery of each player's sound, both individually and as a collective, is evident throughout his career.

In "Hot and Bothered," Ellington's orchestration and tone color skills are on full display. A call-and-response between Bubber Miley's muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing integrates vocal elements with instrumental aspects to create a rich, complementary sound. This technique is further evident in "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)," where Ellington employs Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's muted trombone to introduce the melody, showcasing his ear for tone and his ability to complement his soloists.

Ellington's use of voice to add depth and color to his compositions is a recurring theme throughout his work. His ability to blend vocal and instrumental elements, highlighting individual player's styles and the ensemble's tone, is a hallmark of his innovative approach to creating jazz music.

Since her early teens, an indescribable yearning had plagued her. It was a longing that remained unquenched, even as years passed. At 14, she began to yearn for something, but three years later, at 17, she realized it wasn't an object but a person that she craved. Yet, none of the boys who showed interest in her managed to pique her curiosity. She often pondered this peculiar condition, trying to rationalize it, but all she had were theories that left her unsatisfied. So, she continued to live her life, perpetually questioning her desires.

On this particular day, a peaceful home was disrupted. Her parents, generally serene, rarely argued with her, except when she sought to assert her independence. They were a calm couple, and their vivacious daughter was a stark contrast, making her both charming and good-natured.

Today, however, tranquility was shattered. She heard a sharp cry from the kitchen, her mother's voice echoing with distress. She rushed in, her heart pounding, and found her mother on the floor, groaning. "Mom! What happened?" she exclaimed, kneeling beside her. Her mother, through gritted teeth, instructed her to take her to the hospital. She complied, using her strength from her fitness classes to carry her mother to the car.

The sterile scent of the hospital filled her nostrils as she rushed her mother in, her mind focused solely on helping her. A team of doctors swiftly attended to her, leaving her to wait anxiously.

Her mother had been trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet when she fell off a stool, sustaining an injury.

The investigation aimed to demonstrate that compliance with a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternative Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", correlates with a diminished likelihood of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke incidence, including stroke-related deaths. The aMed diet is an adaptation of the Med diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant-based foods, such as plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, along with reduced intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permissible.

Earlier research has established an inverse relationship between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of overall and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality, while an intervention trial indicated that the Med diet is more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and decreasing the total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in overweight individuals. Prior studies, however, did not focus specifically on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, who had no history of CVD or diabetes, and participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over six intervals between 1984 and 2004, an aMed diet score was calculated from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) that assessed nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of nurses maintained participation throughout the 20-year period. The FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical, hospital, autopsy, or death records. In cases where records were unavailable, cases were classified as "probable" and included, accounting for approximately 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts.

To minimize random variability for individuals and better represent long-term dietary habits, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were computed (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could skew results) by considering age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone replacement therapy, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was employed to examine the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal events.

Increased adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a reduced risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident CHD cases, 1763 incident stroke cases, and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile exhibited a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In the annum of 2007, the United States found itself in the throes of a catastrophic financial calamity. Unemployment surged, the housing sector imploded, and numerous prominent American corporations were left in financial oblivion. This economic downturn continues to this day, prompting the query: whence did this crisis originate, and how may we forestall such occurrences in the future? Simply put, the financial crisis was unleashed by a combination of self-serving and naive political decisions that coerced banks and corporations into issuing subprime loans upon an already fragile and insufficient financial framework. Concurrently, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to guarantee and repack these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, banks found themselves short on capital reserves and managed to pass this turmoil onto the repackaged mortgages they had sold, ultimately spreading the contagion throughout the economy.

The seeds of this financial crisis were sown in 1999 during the Clinton presidency, as the administration sought to secure a second term by bolstering its popularity. To achieve this, lending restrictions were relaxed, setting the stage for the subprime crisis seven years hence. Steven Holmes of the New York Times, in 1999, reported, “Fannie Mae, the nation’s largest mortgage underwriter, faced mounting pressure from the Clinton Administration to extend mortgage loans to low- and moderate-income individuals, and felt the pressure of shareholders to maintain its extraordinary profit growth.”

Holmes accurately prophesied the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, necessitating a government bailout akin to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As expounded in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, imprudent lending would indeed precipitate an economic meltdown.

Numerous factors conspired to plunge the economy into disarray, one of which was the evolving nature of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were extensively employed in the years preceding the crisis, further entangling various sectors of the economy in the housing market. This led to U.S. households and financial markets to become excessively leveraged in the housing sector, making them highly susceptible to even minor price fluctuations.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had invested in mortgage-backed securities found themselves in dire straits. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which constituted approximately 30% of the U.S. GDP. Ultimately, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at a steep discount, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were compelled to convert into commercial banks subject to stringent regulation. Fannie and Freddie, saddled with $5 trillion in mortgage debt, were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, the bridge between the opening act and the main event. The point where you're either soaring on clouds of eloquence or crashing into the abyss of boredom. Dr. Merlin, herself, has been known to let out a few choice expletives when she finds herself stuck in a quagmire of info overload, the kind that's not fun or engaging.

Exposition, dear reader, is not your ally.

You're already aware of the fundamental rule of writing, "Show, Don't Tell." Yet, Dr. Merlin still finds herself tripping over long, unyielding paragraphs where nothing of consequence happens, or worse, too much. It's that little voice in your head urging you to get the background out of the way to get to the good stuff, not to be confused with the other voice whispering that you should share every last detail of your characters' backstories.

Exposition is the act of relaying information to the audience, typically in straightforward prose. In movies, it's that scene where a character dumps a massive amount of information on another character, like a monologue from the "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

Consider this: As you're reading a tale, you're told about a heroine's love story. She met her beloved at a certain place and time, theymarried in a grand ceremony, and her husband was murdered right in front of her. You wouldn't expect this sequence to take up two whole pages, with both characters only uttering a couple of lines of dialogue each. You'd expect the author to delve into the husband's character, showing his love for the heroine through words and actions, and she, in turn, would demonstrate how his presence transformed her life in big and small ways. A proper introduction to the husband's character would make you feel his loss deeply and give you insight into the heroine's thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as seen through his eyes. You'd mourn his death with her, and thus become more invested in her story.

In other words, you'd expect substance, not just a bare-bones narrative: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you must provide that substance. Sometimes, it's tempting to rush past certain details. Perhaps you're introducing a new character, and you know he used to be in the military, now works at a gas station, has been married twice, no children, enjoys fishing on weekends, and secretly dreams of owning the gas station sometime. You'd want to show these details, not just state them.

In two broadcast updates from Columbus, Ohio, an NBC 4 morning segment (August 13, 2011) led with a developing incident in Ashley, Ohio. A man, identified as Shad Hostettler, was arrested for stabbing his spouse; his mug shot was aired, depicting a menacing demeanor. The piece ran briefly, about two minutes, given the fluid nature of the situation.

A separate morning update highlighted a shooting in the Sharon Woods area, involving a young man named Travis Buyers, who was critically injured. Authorities were investigating; no arrests had been made. This story was concise, a pattern I've noticed with minority victims, often receiving less attention than their white counterparts. This lack of coverage is a consistent issue.

The broadcast also touched on a gunshot hole in a Med-Flight helicopter, likely caused by a .22 caliber rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest.

An upcoming weather forecast for the weekend was brief, mentioning afternoon thunderstorms and highs in the mid-to-low eighties. This segment was short, perhaps to pique interest for future updates.

A robbery at a Clime Road UDF store featured a black man, who was dark-skinned and approximately six feet tall, weighing about 150 pounds. The report seemed to emphasize his race, which I found unnecessary.

An additional story detailed Rene Rodriguez, a Hispanic former drug kingpin convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana from Texas to Ohio. While he was sentenced to 300 months, the report noted his ethnicity, which seemed irrelevant.

The connection between siblings is profound, a tether that neither time nor distance can sever. Among its many facets are sentiments like affection, admiration, envy, and spite. Siblings understand each other in ways that others never could, seeing in their brother's eyes a reflection of their own soul. These emotions are most vividly displayed in times of crisis, whether good or ill. When these feelings are laid bare, they come with a price. Part of comprehending the emotional ties of this familial bond is grappling with their repercussions. When one gazes into their brother's eyes, they see not the world's perception of them, but their true self. Their actions and the outcomes of those actions reveal their genuine character. In the novel "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers delve into this theme, along with the tumultuous emotions that accompany it. In a setting rich with vivid description, these two boys embark on an ill-fated journey. Disappointment and pride clash in the story's climax, and only one brother survives. The theme is conveyed through the protagonist's direct portrayal and his interactions with his brother, as well as through the narrator's perspective, which communicates the protagonist's intricate feelings and his view of the world, both of which significantly influence his actions.

The protagonist's actions are fueled by a singular emotion: pride. From their first outing together to their final, fateful journey, the protagonist harbors resentment towards his little brother, Doodle. He envisioned a brother with whom he could share his skills, like holding his breath, running, jumping, or climbing vines in Old Woman Swamp. He dreamed of a brother to race to Horsehead Landing with and to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn. Unfortunately, these aspirations were dashed by Doodle's frail heart. The young protagonist was filled with wild fantasies, only to have them shattered in a moment. He even contemplated harming the small child, considering suffocating him with a pillow. Yet, his heart softened when Doodle merely smiled at him. This display of love was a testament to the protagonist's true feelings, despite his initial thoughts of infanticide. Deep down, he cared for his brother.

The neural matrix, a complex, imaginative data-processing system, has seen its descriptive analogies evolve with technological progress. Initially likened to a wax tablet, then to a scroll, followed by a tome, and lately, to a digital device, these metaphors, while useful, have limitations and can mislead. As your exploration of the brain unfolds, remember the restricted utility of these analogies and their potential pitfalls.
Sensory organs convert physical stimuli, like touch, warmth, sound waves, or light particles, into electrochemical signals, initiating information intake. The brain then continuously converts this data, employing both bottom-up and top-down processing methods. For instance, when viewing an image of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing combines basic details such as color, orientation, and border positions to infer a box. Top-down processing, leveraging earlier decisions from the bottom-up process, accelerates the recognition of the object as a black box versus a box-like void in the white backdrop.
An attentional gate subsequently determines the significance of the signal and the cognitive processes it should engage. In a grass-filled field, your brain processes every blade, yet an efficient attentional gate prevents individual perception unless the signal is deemed noteworthy, like your name in a noisy environment. This process occurs in multiple stages, with the results continuously shaped by attention.
Information processing necessitates storage. Various memory types exist, including sensory, working, and long-term. Encoding varies based on the type of stimulus. Verbal input, for instance, can be structured, referring to visual form, phonemic, relating to sound, or semantic, signifying meaning. Once stored, information must be sustained. Working memory, lasting around 20 seconds, is thought to be maintained by an electrical signal looping through specific neurons. Long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained structurally via certain proteins.
Multiple theories describe how knowledge is organized in the brain, drawing from subjects' memory retrieval, computer science, and neurophysiology. The semantic network theory posits nodes representing concepts, linked based on their relevance. For example, in a semantic network, "chair" connects to "table," which can link to "wooden," and so forth.

Aldous Huxley takes aim at the looming perils of technology and capitalism in his dystopian novel, Brave New World. In this society, collective welfare trumps individuality, and citizens are indoctrinated from birth to prioritize immediate contentment. The populace serves as mere cogs in a larger machine, bound by the World Controller's dictates. Through the lens of Marxist ideology, one discerns Huxley's reservations concerning the burgeoning economic systems of his time. Concepts like homogeneity and reification are evident in his critique, implying that the novel is a commentary on the shortcomings of the emerging capitalist economy.

 Capitalism is lampooned through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. The common folk are kept in the dark about their true economic ties to other classes, fixated instead on personal gain. This is achieved through the ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, a tactic employed in Brave New World. The populace, divided into classes such as Delta and Gamma, have no genuine agency, their desires for consumption and indulgence amplified through hypnopædia. This manipulation is evident in the World Controller's influence. The idea of hegemony, where social classes are dominated by a separate group, is clearly present. The lower classes are oblivious to this manipulation, 'buying into' the ideology that supports capitalism and consumerism. The upper classes, though capable of understanding, often accept their status. Characters like Bernard exemplify this, with few Alphas and Betas doing more than contentedly accepting their role. The interactions between social classes underscore the perceived oppression of capitalism.

The novel presents a world where meaningful relationships are absent. Characters, even major ones, lack depth. Perhaps Huxley implies that the confluence of technology and capitalism stifles free will and expression. Love and intense emotions are nonexistent, replaced by superficial interactions. Men comment on women primarily in terms of their physical attributes, while women discuss their encounters flippantly. Each class' willingness to accept their place in the hierarchy mirrors the socioeconomic impact of capitalism. Their unquestioning obedience suggests a proletariat mindset, content with their superior status so long as they continue to consume and conform.

I've been a student at University Park for approximately two and a half years, or roughly four and a half semesters. Like many, navigating campus can be challenging. My freshman year, I was assigned to an East Halls dorm room, located quite far eastward, save for the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from Stuart Hall to distant locations like the Willard Building, near the campus core, could take up to 25 minutes, particularly on inclement days, which are frequent in State College. An alumni, only slightly older than me, shared that East Halls was once isolated by expansive, unused land. Now, that empty space has been transformed into sports fields, new buildings including the Creamery and Health Services, and surrounding apartment complexes. As campus growth continues, travel between points becomes increasingly cumbersome. A feasible solution? Bicycles! However, merely having bikes won't suffice. Students must use them, and campuses must accommodate them.

My friend recently resumed cycling after a break and commented, "Bikes are fantastic – they're the best way to commute. For a while, it wasn't popular to ride, but it's the most efficient mode of transportation." Bicycling is not only beneficial for health but also the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some exertion can cover 30 miles or more. I now live off-campus, as distant from the center as some dorms. The wisest decision this year was investing in a bike. My classes in Thomas Building, a 25-minute walk from home, can take just 5 minutes by bike, if pedaled quickly. The main issue is Pollock Road, the most direct route to Thomas, which isn't always easy to traverse. Walking is a valid option, but my schedule's too busy for that. Without a bike, walking would be my only reliable transport. Walking to Thomas daily would add 30-40 minutes to my day, roughly 2.5 hours weekly, plus extra time for other classes, appointments, etc.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas. Because each of their arguments is in defense of the same concept, and our challenge is to determine who’s is the better of the two, we must, for sake of brevity, begin with the presumption that they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. To allow for a God-type figure that may not resemble the one in whom our two authors believe would not permit us to appropriately compare their two arguments, as they are essentially in defense of one specific concept of God. That being said, I would suggest that while each of them brings up valid points, neither truly provides a holistic basis for belief in God.
	To illustrate this point, we will first examine the basic argument of St. Anselm. Anselm’s passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith, looking within one’s self to find proof of God. He explains that because God exists within our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive his nonexistence. While this concept, when spelled out in his terminology, is a bit tedious and at times unclear, the basic gist of it is that the proof for God lies within one’s own mind. St. Anselm is suggesting to us that we needn’t go beyond the confines of our own soul to find truth about God, but that the existence of this being is found to be true simply by examining that which we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting that for which there is not an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to within Christian texts as faith.
	This idea is very different from that held by St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas instead suggests that the existence of God can be proven entirely through reason and empirical evidence, with no need for faith of any kind. Such an idea would be beneficial in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, because it would enable the recruiting of new converts without any dependency upon their willingness to accept something that cannot be proven. They could instead be persuaded by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you are told that that you are missing one puzzle piece, and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know of the features and the existence of the missing piece without having to see it.

Many authors use different ways to give their readers a certain feeling or attitude toward
important subjects. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses
many of these different techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an
adjective and a noun together that do not usually fit that way to give readers a certain aura around a
subject. Other times, he applies meaning to a symbol, and then uses it for this same purpose.
Fitzgerald uses this last technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray and red/pink. In
his novel The Great Gatsby F. Scott Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors, namely white/gray and
red/pink then later uses that meaning to give readers a certain reminder of a feeling around an
important object.
The meaning Fitzgerald builds up and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being a bit
nicer and higher class and gray being more older and faded. Fitzgerald sets up this meaning in the
beginning of the novel with constant uses of both. Daisy and Jordan are constantly “in white” (8)—in
fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears “white flannels” (41) to Gatsby’s party, Tom wears
a “white shirt” (36) when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is “powdered milky white” (30). In fact, the
only time people are not wearing white is when Nick is getting his impressions of Gatsby’s party: “the
halls... are gaudy with primary colors” (40). Fitzgerald further defines these two colors in coloring
many common, unimportant subjects these colors: as Nick goes to work, he goes “down the white
chasms of lower New York” (56), the names of people at Gatsby’s parties are now “gray names” (61)
on Nick’s timetable, Catherine’s apartment is “one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses”—
uniformity (28). He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and
Daisy had a “white girlhood” (19) together, there are “gray cars” and “gray land” (23) in the valley of
ashes, the “Italian child” in the railroad is “gray” (26), and the dog-seller is “a gray old man” (27).
After Fitzgerald adds enough meaning to white/gray, he uses them to signify unimportance or
uniformity to certain subjects. This using colors to show readers something first starts with Daisy.
After a long time without any significant use of either of these colors, Fitzgerald comes out describing
Daisy as “dressed in white” in “a little white roadster”; readers begin to see Daisy as less of a character,
more like just a uniform addition, something that Gatsby wants and longs for (74). Fitzgerald uses
more of this technique around Daisy to give this impression of Daisy being a more uniform addition,
for example, there is a “gray haze of Daisy’s fur collar” (18), and she is again in a “white” (115) dress
before Tom and Gatsby’s encounter.

San Diego County is very agriculturally productive, thanks to a mild, sunny climate. Common crops include: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a substantial market for organic community supported agriculture food in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having lengthy waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms also provide tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This is the type of operation that would allow the landowner to gain the benefits of government programs while improving habitat, thus allowing recreational use and creating an opportunity for farm tours and other programs for making money or for educational purposes.  
	In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in plants and wildlife in the area thanks to a lack of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming has greater costs than conventional farming in some ways. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods, while a small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of scale of large operations. Practices not related to organic farming but beneficial to wildlife may also incur greater labor costs, including planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to provide specific conditions such as edge habitat or patches of open ground. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial help or expertise in maximizing both profits and habitat quality.  
The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel adjacent to the town of Potrero, in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It is 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland next to to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still being reviewed, but presently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals. Many are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several species of butterfly, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, such as burrowing owls.
	This area was inhabited by Native Americans for untold centuries and was then settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800's. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and so was probably used for grazing and/or wood production for many of the intervening decades.
	 chose a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to see what options a small farmer might realistically have for mitigating costs and preserving wildlife-friendly operations.  As a model of what somebody farming this land might attempt to achieve, I located an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life.
